(ordinary-world-mornings-nights
  :count 8

  (piece
    :id \"mn-01-a-tuesday-morning\"
    :title \"A Tuesday morning\"
    :prose
    \"The alarm goes off at six-thirty. He hits snooze once. Then he gets
up.

The apartment is dark. He does not turn on lights. He knows the layout.
He can shower without the light on if he wants to. Sometimes he does.

Today he turns on the bathroom light and looks at himself briefly. He
sees an ordinary face. He turns off the light and gets in the shower.

After the shower he dresses. Jeans, t-shirt, sweater over the t-shirt.
Socks. Shoes. He knows where everything is because he laid it out last
night.

He makes toast and eats it standing at the counter. He drinks coffee
from the mug his sister gave him for a birthday four years ago. He
reads a headline on his phone but not the article.

At seven-twenty he leaves. The lock clicks. The hallway is quiet. The
elevator has one other person on it — a woman with a dog. They nod.

Outside it is cold. He turns up his collar. He walks to the subway.
The Tuesday begins.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-02-a-friday-night\"
    :title \"A Friday night\"
    :prose
    \"It's eight-thirty on a Friday. Two friends are on the couch. They
haven't decided if they're going out or staying in.

'Are we going out,' one says.
'Are we,' says the other.
'I don't know.'
'Me neither.'

They order Thai food. The decision is made.

The food arrives forty minutes later. They eat at the coffee table
because that's where they are. They put on a show.

They finish the food. They watch two episodes of the show. Now it's
almost eleven.

'Should we still go out,' one says.
'Should we,' says the other.

They laugh at themselves. They will not go out. That was decided at
eight-thirty; they just didn't want to admit it.

They watch another episode. At twelve one of them falls asleep on the
couch. The other one gets a blanket and puts it over the first one.
Then goes to bed.

Friday nights don't have to be big. Sometimes staying in with a friend
and thai food and three episodes of a show is what a Friday night is.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-03-a-child-cant-sleep\"
    :title \"A child can't sleep\"
    :prose
    \"It's ten forty-five. The seven-year-old is at the top of the stairs.
He is in his pajamas but he is not in bed.

'I can't sleep,' he says.

His mother comes to the bottom of the stairs. 'Bad dream?'

'No. Just can't.'

She goes up. She sits on the edge of his bed. He gets in. She rubs
his back for a minute.

'What are you thinking about,' she asks.

'The volcano book.'

The mother remembers that they read about a volcano yesterday. He was
fascinated and a little scared.

'Volcanoes are far away,' she says. 'Not in Brooklyn.'

'I know.'

'But still?'

'Yeah.'

She sits with him for a while longer. She doesn't say anything else.
He doesn't either. He is not asleep but he is calmer.

She stays until his breathing slows. Then she gets up quietly. She
turns out the light. She closes the door partway.

Downstairs, her partner asks: 'okay?'

'Yeah. Volcano.'

Her partner nods. They both know how kids are.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-04-a-night-shift\"
    :title \"A night shift\"
    :prose
    \"The night nurse comes on at seven pm. She works until seven am.

The first hour is settling in. Reviewing the day nurse's notes.
Checking on patients. Meeting the resident.

By nine most patients are settling. Some are sleeping. Some are
watching TV. Some are anxious.

Ten to two is when the alerts come. The heart monitors beep. The IVs
finish. The call button gets pressed. She moves from room to room. She
knows the shape of each patient in a way the day nurse doesn't have
time to.

Two to five is the quiet middle. The patients are asleep. She catches
up on paperwork. She drinks coffee. She talks with the other night
nurse about small things.

Five to seven the shift ends. Patients start waking. The day nurse
arrives at six-forty-five for handoff.

She leaves at seven. Outside the sun is up. She squints. She walks to
the subway. She sleeps most of the day and comes back at seven pm.

Night shift is a different kind of work. Different rhythm. Different
rewards. Some nurses hate it. She loves it. The quiet middle is what
she likes. And knowing the patients in that specific way.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-05-a-saturday-morning\"
    :title \"A Saturday morning\"
    :prose
    \"Saturday morning is nine-thirty before anyone gets up. The whole
week rushes and Saturday makes up for it by refusing to.

The parents get up first. They make coffee. They eat cereal. They read
the paper — the actual paper, delivered to the door. This is one of
their small extravagances.

The kids come down at ten-thirty in pajamas. They ask about breakfast.
The father makes pancakes because Saturday. There is syrup and there
is fruit.

By eleven-thirty everyone is dressed. They discuss what to do. Park?
Yes. Groceries? Yes, after. Lunch? Maybe out.

They walk to the park. It is a fifteen-minute walk. They talk about
the week. The nine-year-old talks the most. The four-year-old
interrupts. The parents mediate.

At the park, an hour. Swings, slides, running. The nine-year-old
climbs the tree that they are told not to climb. Nobody enforces the
rule too hard.

By one o'clock they are back home. They have groceries. They have
lunch. They have their Saturday.

The rest of the day is unstructured. Maybe a movie. Maybe not. That
is what Saturday afternoons are for.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-06-the-late-late-night\"
    :title \"The late late night\"
    :prose
    \"It is two in the morning. He is in the kitchen making tea. He could
not sleep.

The kettle takes four minutes. He stands by the window. Outside the
street is empty. One car goes by very slowly, then stops at the light
which is red even though there is no traffic. Then it goes.

He pours the tea. He sits at the table.

He drinks the tea. His mind is loud but not focused. The tea is warm.
The kitchen is dim. The refrigerator hums.

He is not doing anything. He is not thinking anything specific. He is
just up.

By three the tea is done. His mind has quieted a little. He goes back
to bed. His partner does not wake up. She rolls over. He lies still.

Ten minutes later he is asleep.

In the morning he will barely remember getting up. He will find the
empty mug in the sink and it will be the only evidence.

Some nights this happens. Not most. But some. He does not fight it.
The tea works.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-07-first-light\"
    :title \"First light\"
    :prose
    \"In June, first light is at four forty-five. The sky is not yet blue.
It is a gray-lavender that has no name. If you are awake for it, you
are usually the only person on your block who is.

The birds start about ten minutes before first light. Small ones,
starting quietly. By first light they are louder. By five they are
what everyone would call birds singing.

If you walk outside at four forty-five in June you find a city that
looks strange. Empty streets. No cars. The rustle of the leaves in
the trees. You can hear a train two miles away.

By five-thirty the light is more visible. By six the sky is proper
blue. By six-thirty the first commuters are on the street.

Most people never see first light. That's fine. It happens every day
whether or not anyone is watching.\")

  (piece
    :id \"mn-08-last-light\"
    :title \"Last light\"
    :prose
    \"In December, last light is at four-thirty in the afternoon. This is
the hardest thing about December. Not the cold. The light going out
so early.

At three-thirty you can feel it coming. The sky is already turning.
The sun is low. Everything gets that late-day slant.

By four the streetlights come on. Some people don't notice. Some people
notice and feel a small sadness. Some people notice and feel nothing.

By four-thirty it is dark. The kids getting out of school walk home
in the dark. The commuters going home walk home in the dark. The
whole afternoon shift ends in the dark.

The stores put on their lights. The subway stations glow. The
apartments have lights in their windows. The city adjusts. It has
done this every December for as long as the city has existed.

By six the darkness is normal. Nobody thinks about it anymore. Winter
begins to feel like winter. There will be short bright days between
storms. There will be days that are just gray from start to finish.
There will be days when the sun is out at three and gone by four-
thirty.

The days will start getting longer by January. Nobody will notice for
a few weeks. By February they will notice. By March they will feel
happy about it.

But right now, in December, last light is early. That's just how it
is.\"))
")
